  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the legal history of money laundering prohibitions:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal anti-money laundering (AML) practices existed historically to combat tax evasion\n- Significant developments emerged in the 20th century, particularly during Prohibition era in the United States\n\n2. Key Milestones:\n- 1970: Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) in the United States - first comprehensive legal framework\n- 1986: Money Laundering Control Act further criminalized money laundering as a federal crime\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established to develop international AML standards\n\n3. International Developments:\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention addressed money laundering related to drug trafficking\n- 1990 Council of Europe Convention expanded legal frameworks\n- Subsequent UN and international treaties progressively strengthened global AML regulations\n\n4. Modern Regulatory Landscape:\n- Increased focus on combating terrorism financing post-9/11\n- Continuously evolving regulations targeting financial crimes\n- Enhanced reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Sophisticated tracking and monitoring technologies\n\n5. Global Compliance:\n- Most developed countries now have comprehensive AML legal frameworks\n- Increasing international cooperation and information sharing\n- Significant penalties for non-compliance\n\nThis overview represents a general progression of money laundering legal history.",
